From 1aa7f8cc455359649060b0ba9cc0e43bcf459f68 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 21:02:38 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 24/25] execute_cmd: bail to fork path for interactive async
 commands

The async-support commit unconditionally allowed `cmd &' through the
spawnve fast path.  In non-interactive shells (the Git test suite
case) this is correct: SIGINT is not delivered, there is no terminal
contending for fd 0, and the regular path's setup_async_signals() /
async_redirect_stdin() machinery is a no-op anyway.

In interactive shells, those calls in the post-fork child matter:

  - setup_async_signals() sets SIGINT and SIGQUIT to SIG_IGN in the
    async child so that Ctrl-C in the parent terminal does not kill
    the background job;
  - async_redirect_stdin() (when CMD_STDIN_REDIR is set and stdin
    has not been explicitly redirected by the user) dup2s fd 0 from
    /dev/null so the background job does not steal the terminal's
    input from the foreground parent.

Cygwin's spawnve gives us no between-fork-and-exec hook to replicate
either effect.  We could approximate setup_async_signals by setting
SIGINT/SIGQUIT to SIG_IGN in the parent, spawnve'ing (the child
inherits SIG_IGN, which the POSIX exec rules preserve across exec),
and restoring -- but this opens a brief window where signals
delivered to the parent are silently lost.  We could approximate
async_redirect_stdin by adding a save/dup2/restore around fd 0, like
the pipe-input path -- but it changes parent behavior in subtle
ways.  Both deserve their own treatment in follow-up commits.

For now, bail out of the fast path when `async && interactive_shell'.
This preserves the correctness of background jobs in interactive
shells while keeping the speedup for non-interactive scripts (where
both setup functions are no-ops anyway).  Test scripts and the Git
test suite continue to use the fast path for async commands; only
people typing `cmd &' at an interactive prompt go through fork.

Assisted-by: Claude Opus 4.7
Signed-off-by: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
---
 execute_cmd.c | 11 +++++++++++
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+)

diff --git a/execute_cmd.c b/execute_cmd.c
index 73cce6f..5312ace 100644
--- a/execute_cmd.c
+++ b/execute_cmd.c
@@ -6308,6 +6308,17 @@ fast_spawn_command (char *command, WORD_LIST *words,
   /* Conditions we don't yet handle.  Bail out and let make_child do it. */
   if (cmdflags & CMD_NO_FORK)
     return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
+  if (async && interactive_shell)
+    /* In interactive shells, the regular fork path runs
+       setup_async_signals() in the post-fork child to make the
+       background job ignore SIGINT and SIGQUIT, and (when
+       CMD_STDIN_REDIR is set and stdin is not explicitly redirected)
+       redirects stdin to /dev/null so the background job does not
+       compete for the terminal's input.  Cygwin's spawnve gives us
+       no between-fork-and-exec hook to replicate either effect.  In
+       non-interactive shells (the test-suite path) those effects do
+       not matter, so we keep the fast path enabled there. */
+    return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
   if (redirects && !fast_spawn_redirect_supported (redirects))
     return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
 
